T1  - The payment system and domestic exchange rates: Technological versus institutional change
AU  - Garbade, Kenneth D.
AU  - Silber, William L.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 5
IS  - 1
SP  - 1
EP  - 22
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(79)90021-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393279900217
AB  - This paper presents an institutional and empirical description of domestic exchange in the United States between 1840 and 1918, within the context of the structural evolution of the payments mechanism. Just as the need to tender payments internationally gives rise to foreign exchange, so the necessity for inter-regional payments gives rise to domestic exchange. Rates on domestic exchange flactuated within limits defined by the cost of shipping gold or currency between cities within the United States. The variability of these rates depended on the cost of transportation and on the sophistication of institutional arrangements of the payments system. Our paper seeks to assess the relative importance of these two factors for the diminution of domestic exchange rates over the period of observation. In addition, we try to isolate the welfare implications of improvements in the payments system, in particular, the importance of the diminution in exchange rates for inter-regional integration of the short-term money markets.
ER  - 

